ChiNode.Notes: Specifies one limit value for a Measurement. A Measurement typically has several limits that are kept together by the LimitSet class. The actual meaning and use of a Limit instance (i.e., if it is an alarm or warning limit or if it is a high or low limit) is not captured in the Limit class. However the name of a Limit instance may indicate both meaning and use.

ChiNode.creator: admin
ChiNode.Name: LimitSet
ChiNode.Notes: Specifies a set of Limits that are associated with a Measurement. A Measurement may have several LimitSets corresponding to seasonal or other changing conditions. The condition is captured in the name and description attributes. The same LimitSet may be used for several Measurements. In particular percentage limits are used this way.

ChiValue.Name: isPercentageLimits
ChiValue.Notes: Tells if the limit values are in percentage of normalValue or the specified Unit for Measurements and Controls.

ChiNode.creator: admin
ChiNode.Name: Measurement
ChiNode.Notes:
A Measurement represents any measured, calculated or non-measured non-calculated quantity. Any piece of equipment may contain Measurements, e.g. a substation may have temperature measurements and door open indications, a transformer may have oil temperature and tank pressure measurements, a bay may contain a number of power flow measurements and a Breaker may contain a switch status measurement.
The PSR - Measurement association is intended to capture this use of Measurement and is included in the naming hierarchy based on EquipmentContainer. The naming hierarchy typically has Measurements as leafs, e.g. Substation-VoltageLevel-Bay-Switch-Measurement.
Some Measurements represent quantities related to a particular sensor location in the network, e.g. a voltage transformer (PT) at a busbar or a current transformer (CT) at the bar between a breaker and an isolator. The sensing position is not captured in the PSR - Measurement association. Instead it is captured by the Measurement - Terminal association that is used to define the sensing location in the network topology. The location is defined by the connection of the Terminal to ConductingEquipment.
Two possible paths exist: 1) Measurement-Terminal- ConnectivityNode-Terminal-ConductingEquipment 2) Measurement-Terminal-ConductingEquipment
Alternative 2 is the only allowed use.
When the sensor location is needed both Measurement-PSR and Measurement-Terminal are used. The Measurement-Terminal association is never used alone.

ChiNode.creator: admin
ChiNode.Name: MeasurementType
ChiNode.Notes: Specifies the type of Measurement, e.g. IndoorTemperature, OutDoorTemperature, BusVoltage, GeneratorVoltage, LineFlow etc. The MeasurementType.name shall be unique among all specified types and describe the type. The MeasurementType.aliasName is meant to be used for localization.

ChiNode.creator: admin
ChiNode.Name: MeasurementValue
ChiNode.Notes: The current state for a measurement. A state value is an instance of a measurement from a specific source. Measurements can be associated with many state values, each representing a different source for the measurement.

ChiValue.Name: sensorAccuracy
ChiValue.Notes: The limit, expressed as a percentage of the sensor maximum, that errors will not exceed when the sensor is used under reference conditions.

ChiValue.Name: timeStamp
ChiValue.Notes: The time when the value was last updated

ChiNode.creator: admin
ChiNode.Name: MeasurementValueQuality
ChiNode.Notes: Measurement quality flags. Bits 0-10 are defined for substation automation in draft IEC 61850 part 7-3. Bits 11-15 are reserved for future expansion by that document. Bits 16-31 are reserved for EMS applications.

ChiNode.creator: admin
ChiNode.Name: MeasurementValueSource
ChiNode.Notes: MeasurementValueSource describes the alternative sources updating a MeasurementValue. User conventions for how to use the MeasurementValueSource attributes are described in the introduction to IEC 61970-301.

ChiNode.creator: admin
ChiNode.Name: Quality61850
ChiNode.Notes: Quality flags in this class are as defined in IEC 61850, except for estimatorReplaced, which has been included in this class for convenience.

ChiValue.Name: badReference
ChiValue.Notes: Measurement value may be incorrect due to a reference being out of calibration.

ChiValue.Name: estimatorReplaced
ChiValue.Notes: Value has been replaced by State Estimator. estimatorReplaced is not an IEC61850 quality bit but has been put in this class for convenience.

ChiValue.Name: failure
ChiValue.Notes: This identifier indicates that a supervision function has detected an internal or external failure, e.g. communication failure.

ChiValue.Name: oldData
ChiValue.Notes: Measurement value is old and possibly invalid, as it has not been successfully updated during a specified time interval.

ChiValue.Name: operatorBlocked
ChiValue.Notes: Measurement value is blocked and hence unavailable for transmission.

ChiValue.Name: oscillatory
ChiValue.Notes: To prevent some overload of the communication it is sensible to detect and suppress oscillating (fast changing) binary inputs. If a signal changes in a defined time (tosc) twice in the same direction (from 0 to 1 or from 1 to 0) then oscillation is detected and the detail quality identifier "oscillatory" is set. If it is detected a configured numbers of transient changes could be passed by. In this time the validity status "questionable" is set. If after this defined numbers of changes the signal is still in the oscillating state the value shall be set either to the opposite state of the previous stable value or to a defined default value. In this case the validity status "questionable" is reset and "invalid" is set as long as the signal is oscillating. If it is configured such that no transient changes should be passed by then the validity status "invalid" is set immediately in addition to the detail quality identifier "oscillatory" (used for status information only).

ChiValue.Name: outOfRange
ChiValue.Notes: Measurement value is beyond a predefined range of value.

ChiValue.Name: overFlow
ChiValue.Notes: Measurement value is beyond the capability of being represented properly. For example, a counter value overflows from maximum count back to a value of zero.

ChiValue.Name: source
ChiValue.Notes: Source gives information related to the origin of a value. The value may be acquired from the process, defaulted or substituted.

ChiValue.Name: suspect
ChiValue.Notes: A correlation function has detected that the value is not consitent with other values. Typically set by a network State Estimator.

ChiValue.Name: test
ChiValue.Notes: Measurement value is transmitted for test purposes.

ChiValue.Name: validity
ChiValue.Notes: Validity of the measurement value.

ChiValue.Name: maxValue

ChiValue.Name: minValue

ChiNode.Name: ValueAliasSet
ChiNode.Notes: Describes the translation of a set of values into a name and is intendend to facilitate cusom translations. Each ValueAliasSet has a name, description etc. A specific Measurement may represent a discrete state like Open, Closed, Intermediate etc. This requires a translation from the MeasurementValue.value number to a string, e.g. 0->"Invalid", 1->"Open", 2->"Closed", 3->"Intermediate". Each ValueToAlias member in ValueAliasSet.Value describe a mapping for one particular value to a name.

ChiNode.creator: admin
ChiNode.Name: ValueToAlias
ChiNode.Notes: Describes the translation of one particular value into a name, e.g. 1->"Open"

ChiValue.Name: value
ChiValue.Notes: The value that is mapped

ChiNode.Name: ApparentPowerLimit

ChiNode.Name: CurrentLimit

ChiValue.Name: value

ChiNode.creator: admin
ChiNode.Name: OperationalLimit
ChiNode.Notes: A value associated with a specific kind of limit.

ChiValue.Name: type
ChiValue.Notes: Used to specify high/low and limit levels.

ChiNode.creator: admin
ChiNode.Name: OperationalLimitSet
ChiNode.Notes: A set of limits associated with equipmnet. Sets of limits might apply to a specific temperature, or season for example. A set of limits may contain may different severiteis of limit levels that would apply to the same equipment. The set may contain limits of different types such as apparent power and current limits or high and low voltage limits that are logically applied together as a set.

ChiNode.creator: admin
ChiNode.Name: OperationalLimitType
ChiNode.Notes: A type of limit. The meaning of a specific limit is described in this class.

ChiValue.Name: acceptableDuration
ChiValue.Notes: The nominal acceptable duration of the limit. Limits are commonly expressed in terms of the a time limit for which the limit is normally acceptable. The actual acceptable duration of a specific limit may depend on other local factors such as temperature or wind speed.

ChiValue.Name: direction
ChiValue.Notes: The direction of the limit.

ChiNode.creator: admin
ChiNode.Name: VoltageLimit
ChiNode.Notes: Operational limit applied to voltage.

ChiValue.Name: value
ChiValue.Notes: Limit on voltage. High or low limit depends on the OperatoinalLimit.limitKind

Package.Name: Outage
Package.Notes: An extension to the Core and Wires packages that models information on the current and planned network configuration. These entities are optional within typical network applications.

ChiNode.Name: ClearanceTag
ChiNode.Notes: A clearance tag that is used to authorize and schedule work on conducting equipment in the field. Tagged equipment is not available for commercial service.

ChiValue.Name: authorityName

ChiValue.Name: deenergizeReqFlag

ChiValue.Name: groundReqFlag

ChiValue.Name: phaseCheckReqFlag

ChiValue.Name: tagIssueTime

ChiValue.Name: workDescription

ChiValue.Name: workEndTime
ChiValue.Notes: The time at which the clearance tag is scheduled to be removed

ChiValue.Name: workStartTime

ChiNode.creator: admin
ChiNode.Name: ClearanceTagType

ChiNode.creator: admin
ChiNode.Name: OutageSchedule
ChiNode.Notes: The period of time that a piece of equipment is out of service, for example, for maintenance or testing; including the equipment's active power rating while under maintenance. The X-axis represents absolute time and the Y-axis represents the equipment's available rating while out of service.

ChiNode.creator: admin
ChiNode.Name: SwitchingOperation
ChiNode.Notes: A SwitchingOperation is used to define individual switch operations for an OutageSchedule. This OutageSchedule may be associated with another item of Substation such as a Transformer, Line, or Generator; or with the Switch itself as a PowerSystemResource. A Switch may be referenced by many OutageSchedules.

ChiValue.Name: newState
ChiValue.Notes: The switch position that shall result from this SwitchingOperation

ChiValue.Name: operationTime

Package.Name: Protection
Package.Notes: An extension to the Core and Wires packages that models information for protection equipment such as relays. These entities are used within training simulators and distribution network fault location applications.

ChiNode.creator: admin
ChiNode.Name: CurrentRelay
ChiNode.Notes: A device that checks current flow values in any direction or designated direction

ChiValue.Name: currentLimit1
ChiValue.Notes: Current limit #1 for inverse time pickup

ChiValue.Name: currentLimit2
ChiValue.Notes: Current limit #2 for inverse time pickup

ChiValue.Name: currentLimit3
ChiValue.Notes: Current limit #3 for inverse time pickup

ChiValue.Name: inverseTimeFlag
ChiValue.Notes: Set true if the current relay has inverse time characteristic.

ChiValue.Name: timeDelay1
ChiValue.Notes: Inverse time delay #1 for current limit #1

ChiValue.Name: timeDelay2
ChiValue.Notes: Inverse time delay #2 for current limit #2

ChiValue.Name: timeDelay3
ChiValue.Notes: Inverse time delay #3 for current limit #3

ChiNode.creator: admin
ChiNode.Name: ProtectionEquipment
ChiNode.Notes: An electrical device designed to respond to input conditions in a prescribed manner and after specified conditions are met to cause contact operation or similar abrupt change in associated electric control circuits, or simply to display the detected condition. Protection equipment are associated with conducting equipment and usually operate circuit breakers.

ChiValue.Name: highLimit
ChiValue.Notes: The maximum allowable value.

ChiValue.Name: lowLimit
ChiValue.Notes: The minimum allowable value.

ChiValue.Name: powerDirectionFlag
ChiValue.Notes: Direction same as positive active power flow value.

ChiValue.Name: relayDelayTime
ChiValue.Notes: The time delay from detection of abnormal conditions to relay operation.

ChiNode.creator: admin
ChiNode.Name: RecloseSequence
ChiNode.Notes: A reclose sequence (open and close) is defined for each possible reclosure of a breaker.

ChiValue.Name: recloseDelay
ChiValue.Notes: Indicates the time lapse before the reclose step will execute a reclose.

ChiValue.Name: recloseStep
ChiValue.Notes: Indicates the ordinal position of the reclose step relative to other steps in the sequence.

ChiNode.creator: admin
ChiNode.Name: SynchrocheckRelay
ChiNode.Notes: A device that operates when two AC circuits are within the desired limits of frequency, phase angle, and voltage, to permit or to cause the paralleling of these two circuits. Used to prevent the paralleling of non-synchronous topological islands.

ChiValue.Name: maxAngleDiff
ChiValue.Notes: The maximum allowable voltage vector phase angle difference across the open device

ChiValue.Name: maxFreqDiff
ChiValue.Notes: The maximum allowable frequency difference across the open device

ChiValue.Name: maxVoltDiff
ChiValue.Notes: The maximum allowable difference voltage across the open device

Package.Name: SCADA
Package.Notes:
Contains entities to model information used by Supervisory Control and Data Acquisition (SCADA) applications. Supervisory control supports operator control of equipment, such as opening or closing a breaker. Data acquisition gathers telemetered data from various sources. The subtypes of the Telemetry entity deliberately match the UCA and IEC 61850 definitions.
This package also supports alarm presentation but it is not expected to be used by other applications.

ChiNode.creator: admin
ChiNode.Name: CommunicationLink
ChiNode.Notes: The connection to remote units is through one or more communication links. Reduntant links may exist. The CommunicationLink class inherit PowerSystemResource. The intention is to allow CommunicationLinks to have Measurements. These Measurements can be used to model link status as operational, out of service, unit failure etc.

ChiNode.creator: admin
ChiNode.Name: RemoteControl
ChiNode.Notes: Remote controls are ouputs that are sent by the remote unit to actuators in the process.

ChiValue.Name: actuatorMaximum
ChiValue.Notes: The maximum set point value accepted by the remote control point.

ChiValue.Name: actuatorMinimum
ChiValue.Notes: The minimum set point value accepted by the remote control point.

ChiValue.Name: remoteControlled
ChiValue.Notes: Set to true if the actuator is remotely controlled.

ChiNode.creator: admin
ChiNode.Name: RemotePoint
ChiNode.Notes: For a RTU remote points correspond to telemetered values or control outputs. Other units (e.g. control centers) usually also contain calculated values.

ChiNode.creator: admin
ChiNode.Name: RemoteSource
ChiNode.Notes: Remote sources are state variables that are telemetered or calculated within the remote unit.

ChiValue.Name: sensorMaximum
ChiValue.Notes: The maximum value the telemetry item can return.

ChiValue.Name: sensorMinimum
ChiValue.Notes: The minimum value the telemetry item can return.

ChiValue.Name: scanInterval
ChiValue.Notes: The time interval between scans.

ChiValue.Name: deadband
ChiValue.Notes: The smallest change in value to be reported.

ChiNode.creator: admin
ChiNode.Name: RemoteUnit
ChiNode.Notes: A remote unit can be a RTU, IED, substation control system, control center etc. The communication with the remote unit can be through various standard protocols (e.g. IEC 61870, IEC 61850) or non standard protocols (e.g. DNP, RP570 etc.). A remote unit contain remote data points that might be telemetered, collected or calculated. The RemoteUnit class inherit PowerSystemResource. The intention is to allow RemotUnits to have Measurements. These Measurements can be used to model unit status as operational, out of service, unit failure etc.

ChiValue.Name: remoteUnitType
ChiValue.Notes: Type of remote unit.

Package.Name: Topology
Package.Notes: An extension to the Core Package that in association with the Terminal class models Connectivity, that is the physical definition of how equipment is connected together. In addition it models Topology, that is the logical definition of how equipment is connected via closed switches. The Topology definition is independent of the other electrical characteristics.

ChiNode.creator: admin
ChiNode.Name: BusNameMarker
ChiNode.Notes: Used to apply user standard names to topology buses. Typically used for "bus/branch" case generation. Associated with one or more ConnectivityNodes that are normally a part of the bus name. The associated ConnectivityNodes are to be connected by non-retained switches. For a ring bus station configuration, all busbar connectivity nodes in the ring are typically associated. For a breaker and a half scheme, both busbars would be associated. For a ring bus, all busbars would be associated. For a "straight" busbar configuration, only the main connectivity node at the busbar would be associated. Bus/Branch bus naming specificaiton static model.

ChiNode.creator: admin
ChiNode.Name: ConnectivityNode
ChiNode.Notes: Connectivity nodes are points where terminals of conducting equipment are connected together with zero impedance. Switch/Node static Model

ChiNode.creator: admin
ChiNode.Name: TopologicalIsland
ChiNode.Notes: An electrically connected subset of the network. Topological islands can change as the current network state changes (i.e., disconnect switches, breakers, etc. change state).

ChiNode.creator: admin
ChiNode.Name: TopologicalNode
ChiNode.Notes: A set of connectivity nodes that, in the current network state, are connected together through any type of closed switches, including jumpers. Topological nodes can change as the current network state changes (i.e., switches, breakers, etc. change state). Bus/Branch calculated Model

ChiValue.Name: energized
ChiValue.Notes: True if node energized

ChiValue.Name: loadCarrying
ChiValue.Notes: True if node is load carrying

ChiValue.Name: netInjectionP
ChiValue.Notes: Net injection active power

ChiValue.Name: netInjectionQ
ChiValue.Notes: Net injection reactive power

ChiValue.Name: observabilityFlag
ChiValue.Notes: The observability status of the node.

ChiValue.Name: phaseAngle
ChiValue.Notes: Phase angle of node

ChiValue.Name: voltage
ChiValue.Notes: Voltage of node

ChiNode.creator: admin
ChiNode.Name: ACLineSegment
ChiNode.Notes: A wire or combination of wires, with consistent electrical characteristics, building a single electrical system, used to carry alternating current between points in the power system.

ChiNode.creator: admin
ChiNode.Name: Breaker
ChiNode.Notes: A mechanical switching device capable of making, carrying, and breaking currents under normal circuit conditions and also making, carrying for a specified time, and breaking currents under specified abnormal circuit conditions e.g. those of short circuit.

ChiValue.Name: inTransitTime
ChiValue.Notes: The transition time from open to close.

ChiValue.Name: ratedCurrent
ChiValue.Notes: Fault interrupting current rating.

ChiNode.creator: admin
ChiNode.Name: BusbarSection
ChiNode.Notes:
A conductor, or group of conductors, with negligible impedance, that serve to connect other conducting equipment within a single substation.
Voltage measurements are typically obtained from VoltageTransformers that are connected to busbar sections. A bus bar section may have many physical terminals but for analysis is modelled with exactly one logical terminal.

ChiNode.creator: admin
ChiNode.Name: CompositeSwitch
ChiNode.Notes:
A model of a set of individual Switches normally enclosed within the same cabinet and possibly with interlocks that restrict the combination of switch positions. These are typically found in medium voltage distribution networks.
A CompositeSwitch could represent a Ring-Main-Unit (RMU), or pad-mounted switchgear, with primitive internal devices such as an internal bus-bar plus 3 or 4 internal switches each of which may individually be open or closed. A CompositeSwitch and a set of contained Switches can also be used to represent a multi-position switch e.g. a switch that can connect a circuit to Ground, Open or Busbar.

ChiValue.Name: compositeSwitchType

ChiNode.creator: admin
ChiNode.Name: StaticVarCompensator
ChiNode.Notes:
A facility for providing variable and controllable shunt reactive power. The SVC typically consists of a stepdown transformer, filter, thyristor-controlled reactor, and thyristor-switched capacitor arms.
The SVC may operate in fixed MVar output mode or in voltage control mode. When in voltage control mode, the output of the SVC will be proportional to the deviation of voltage at the controlled bus from the voltage setpoint. The SVC characteristic slope defines the proportion. If the voltage at the controlled bus is equal to the voltage setpoint, the SVC MVar output is zero.

ChiValue.Name: capacitiveRating
ChiValue.Notes: Maximum available capacitive reactive power

ChiValue.Name: inductiveRating
ChiValue.Notes: Maximum available inductive reactive power

ChiValue.Name: sVCControlMode
ChiValue.Notes: SVC control mode.

ChiValue.Name: slope
ChiValue.Notes: The characteristics slope of an SVC defines how the reactive power output changes in proportion to the difference between the regulated bus voltage and the voltage setpoint.

ChiValue.Name: voltageSetPoint
ChiValue.Notes: The reactive power output of the SVC is proportional to the difference between the voltage at the regulated bus and the voltage setpoint. When the regulated bus voltage is equal to the voltage setpoint, the reactive power output is zero.

Reservation fo CBM by a load serving entity allows that entity to reduce its installed generating capacity below that which may otherwise have been necessary without interconnections to meet its generation reliability requirements.

ChiNode.creator: admin
ChiNode.Name: SchedulingCoordinator
ChiNode.Notes: In certain ISO/RTO operations, market participants are represented by Scheduling Coordinators (SCs) that are registered with the ISO/RTO. One participant can register multiple SCs with the ISO/RTO. Many participants can do business with the ISO/RTO using a single SC. Each generator resource can only be scheduled by one SC. One SC can schedule multiple generators. A load scheduling point can be used by multiple SCs. Each SC can schedule load at multiple scheduling points. Each SC can have more than one load schedule at any load scheduling point as long as each load schedule at the same load scheduling point has a separate resource ID and settlement-quality meter. An inter-tie scheduling point can be used by multiple SCs. Each SC can schedule interchange at multiple inter-tie scheduling points. An SC can have multiple interchange schedules at the same inter-tie scheduling point by assigning a unique interchange identifier to each interchange schedule.
